"use strict";(self.webpackChunksimple_scss_utilities=self.webpackChunksimple_scss_utilities||[]).push([[7336],{9748:function(e,t,n){n.r(t);var a=n(4552),o=n(1504),s=n(1548);const i=function(e){let{children:t}=e;const n=Object.assign({main:"main"},(0,a.MN)());return o.createElement(s.c,null,o.createElement(n.main,{className:"p-xl"},t))};function l(e){const t=Object.assign({h1:"h1",h4:"h4",p:"p"},(0,a.MN)(),e.components);return o.createElement(o.Fragment,null,o.createElement(t.h1,null,"About Simple SCSS Utilities"),"\n",o.createElement(t.h4,null,"Why did I make this thing?"),"\n",o.createElement("div",{className:"max-w-42 mx-auto font-lg line-height-xl mt-xl"},o.createElement(t.p,null,"We all know a naive approach to styles can quite easily lead someone down a path of unattractive levels of disorganization and big, bloated stylesheets. To solve this problem, frameworks and various systems gradually emerged."),o.createElement(t.p,null,'By far my favorite approach was the concept of utility classes. When I first encountered them, it just felt "right". TailwindCSS became my favorite framework immediately.'),o.createElement(t.p,null,"But there were other things I liked too. I liked SCSS, and I liked using SCSS modules. I liked writing my own stuff. Wouldn't it be nice (for me) if everything I liked just could work together?"),o.createElement(t.p,null,'Also, why do frameworks try to do everything? To me it feels kind of weird when a framework wants to do everything. Sometimes I kinda want to write my own styles. And I want to do them with scss and scss modules. Combining these with tailwind never felt, well, "proper" so to speak, at least to me.'),o.createElement(t.p,null,"Inspired by an excellent tutorial series I watched one day, I realized it wouldn't be too tough to write my own set of SCSS utility classes."),o.createElement(t.p,null,"I thought it would be nice, at least for my tastes, to sort of combine all the stuff I like in my approach to styles, and agrees with my own feeling that maybe a framework should encourage people to take liberties. It's just more fun, in my opinion."),o.createElement(t.p,null,'Expanding on the tutorial, and sort of copying tailwind\'s apparoach to responsive and psuedo classes, I made a set of SCSS files that generate enough utility classes to handle maybe 75-85% of the more "common" style rules I would use.'),o.createElement(t.p,null,"It wasn't a huge project. I'm estimating this documentation is probably 10 times the work as writing the actual framework!"),o.createElement(t.p,null,"But I thought it was useful enough to build, put on my github, and document. If I'm the only person that ever uses these classes, so be it. But I'm satisfied with the result."),o.createElement(t.p,null,"Made for people who are comfortable with SCSS, one can dive right in the files and edit just about anything. Change the colors. Add/remove breakpoints. And although the CSS these files generates are huge, purging is relatively fast and simple."),o.createElement(t.p,null,"And since it's just SCSS files, it's not \"wrong\" to combine it with any other approach you want. It's just utility classes. Use it to cut down on the boilerplate and then use whatever else you want! I like to combine it with scss modules for any components, and then one more, very lean, very nice stylesheet for any general styles. In fact, for this entire site (aside from the front page banner), I used 4 lines of custom SCSS."),o.createElement(t.p,null,"If you're looking for a framework that combines SCSS with utility classes, is documented, and designed to be as customizable as I can figure out, why not give the docs a glance and see if it's right for you?"),o.createElement(t.p,null,"Tldr: I was bored and it seemed like a good project.")))}t.default=function(e){return void 0===e&&(e={}),o.createElement(i,e,o.createElement(l,e))}}}]);
